<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written submission from ElecInfo Ltd</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:18pt 0pt 4.5pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center; text-indent:-36pt"><a name="_Toc369879835"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ElecInfo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Ltd </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCLG Electrical Competent Person Schemes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">May I start by stating I have an interest in NAPIT, as a duly elected representative of the NAPIT Trade Association nationally and for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ElectricSafe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.   I am not permitted by NAPIT Group to express the views of the NAPIT members I represent</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, or that of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ElectricSafe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in public</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The  information below is my personal opinion based on speaking to Electrical contractors, Electricians (The Trade) and their customers the Public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I have watched with dismay as the Committee has tried to extract from the DCLG Part P Competent Person Schemes what they actually provide to the public. The information below is provided to assist the committee in that process.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">When asked, “What policies and procedures does DCLG have to ensure that when a Part P Scheme speaks on behalf of its members or registered enterprises, that the information is accurate and representative.” They answered, </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Competent Person Schemes are independent bodies authorised by DCLG for a particular purpose. They are accountable to their members but the Department does not have the resources or control mechanisms to ensure that what a competent person scheme operator says or does is always accurate or representative of the views of its members.”</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Electrical Safety Council in their opening statement in February 2012 stated that there had been a reduction in fires of 17.5%, the trade was puzzled by this, as we had been told that there were no statistics.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The fire statistics table attached</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> indicate that there has not been a reduction in fires, but a steady Year on Year increase in electrical distribution fires, with an increase of over 30%  from the year before the introduction of Part P Schemes to 2011/12.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">At the 27</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> February, 2012 oral evidence session, the Minister Andrew </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Stunell</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> would not fully support the statement.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q85 Mark </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Pawsey</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Wouldn’t you agree, Minister, that Part P has been working, because the incidence of fires attributed to mains wiring, which I understand Part P relates to, has declined from 1,057 in 2004 to 872 in 2008? Isn’t that an indication that Part P has been effective?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Andrew </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Stunell</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> It is certainly an indication that something has been effective. Several things have worked to achieve that. It is certainly not part of our case that Part P has not been effective; it is about whether it has been </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">proportionate. Actually, the much more widespread use of circuit breakers has probably had quite a lot to do with that as well. Of course, I do not think the figures distinguish whether the balance of fires that are still occurring is mostly in property that has been subject to Part P or, in fact, in property that has not been touched since 2005 and to which Part P would not apply. I certainly acknowledge that there has been an improvement, but we need to be careful in attributing specific improvement to specific measures.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The other area defining the success of Part P Schemes was membership numbers, when the basis of Competence was set at just a week’s course it is difficult to equate safety for someone working in a home, with that level of knowledge and experience. These short course people are known throughout the trade as “</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Five day Wonders</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">”, the standards of work carried out by many are deplorable.  The current standard is 18 days training and experience, NAPIT do set a higher standard for Qualifications than other Schemes. There should be a more professional entry route for people entering the trade.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">So who sets standards of competence for electricians, the EAS committee does, this committee has been mentioned several times. The Schemes themselves set the standards in this committee, it is not an Institution of Engineering and Technology Committee (IET) they do not approve the standards, they only provide administration and secretarial support.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The publics expectation is that someone  registered with a Competent Person Scheme entering their home is a Competent Qualified Electrician, this is not the case.   The majority of people joining Schemes require only a C&amp;G2382 qualification that proves they can look up a regulation, consisting of  multiple choice questions and the regulation BS7671 book is available to them. There is a requirement to have electrical design competence,  but no requirement to provide evidence. Then UKAS accredits them as Competent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The words Competent, Electrician, and Qualified do not appear on a members certification, as a legal document why is this?</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Schemes only require one person, per company, to be assessed by them, are the rest Competent,  who knows?</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The complaints procedures for the public, does not include the total number of complaints received, the Schemes state complaints are low. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Some Schemes refuse to accept a complaint from a Competent Electrician, only  a Competent Electrician knows if electrical work is safe or not. The request for a more robust complaints procedure for the public by the committee has still not materialised.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It was a requirement to insure </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">notifiable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> work, are the public insured now </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">notifiable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> work has been slashed?</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The public are still responsible for the work of Scheme members, what responsibilities do UKAS accredited Schemes have for the work carried out by their members?</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Public and Trade fund the whole Competent Person Scheme Industry, but we have negligible influence on policy, funding or standards.  A Gas Safe style system looks increasingly attractive from a commercial view point Gas Safe £186, NAPIT £408, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Certsure</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> £444, per annum.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Trade cannot understand why the ESC, ECA NICEIC, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Certsure</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ascertiva</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, Electrical Safety Register are before the committee as separate organisations when they are interlinked at company and director level.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The debate about the two new registers is about Money. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ElectricSafe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> register is open and the Electrical Safety Register is closed to their members only, the government should take ownership of the name, but they are unwilling, I presume there are legal restraints on who carries the responsibility for Schemes actions which is understandable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Schemes have had many opportunities to presented the full picture, but have declined for their own reasons, the above is presented to help the Committee.  The trade appreciates the work the committee has done to uncover the various aspects of the dangerously flawed system.  My trade has had enough, I would welcome the opportunity to assist the Committee further. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are funding the whole sorry mess and feel that are funding should contribute to a more accountable system for public safety.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Table 3 in </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/36503/FSGB_2011-12_Time_Series_Tables_1a_-16.xls"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Fire statistics Grea</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> Britain 2011 to 2012: tables 1a-16</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (excel spreadsheet) published on the </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-statistics-great-britain-2011-to-2012"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Communities and Local Governme</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">n</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">t Department website</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>